Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation with a confirmation dialog:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` and use the `Shell.BackButtonBehavior`:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            // Fire-and-forget the async dialog; return true to cancel navigation now
            ConfirmDiscardAsync();
            return true; // cancels the default back navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed(); // allow normal navigation
    }

    private async Task ConfirmDiscardAsync()
    {
        bool discard = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (discard)
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

> `OnBackButtonPressed` handles the **hardware/OS back button** (Android). Returning `true` cancels navigation.

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button (Shell toolbar):**

In your XAML, use `Shell.BackButtonBehavior` to replace the default arrow with a "Cancel" button that runs the same logic:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
             Title="Edit Product">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then in your view model (or code-behind):

```csharp
public ICommand CancelCommand { get; }

public EditProductPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();

    CancelCommand = new Command(async () =>
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
            await ConfirmDiscardAsync();
        else
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    });

    BindingContext = this; // if not using a separate VM
}
```

**Key points:**
- `OnBackButtonPressed` → handles Android/hardware back.
- `BackButtonBehavior` → handles the Shell navigation bar button, lets you customize text and command.
- Both paths funnel through the same `ConfirmDiscardAsync` logic so behavior is consistent.
